Definition (defsum):
  for all v0, (for all v1, (if v0 is a set and v1 is a set then for all v2, ((v2 is equal to v0 \oplus v1) iff (v2 is a set and for all v3, (if v3 is an object then (v3 is an element of v2 iff for some v4, (v4 is an element of v0 and for some v5, (v5 is an element of v1 and v3 is equal to v4 + v5))))))))

Definition (defsint):
  for all v0, (for all v1, (if v0 is a set and v1 is a set then for all v2, ((v2 is equal to v0 \cap v1) iff (v2 is a set and for all v3, (if v3 is an object then (v3 is an element of v2 iff (v3 is an element of v0 and v3 is an element of v1)))))))

Definition (defideal):
  for all v0, ((v0 is an ideal) iff (v0 is a set and for all v1, (if v1 is an element of v0 then ((for all v2, (if v2 is an element of v0 then v1 + v2 is an element of v0)) and for all v2, (if v2 is an object then v2 \cdot v1 is an element of v0)))))

Theorem (idesum):
  for all v0, (for all v1, (if v0 is an ideal and v1 is an ideal then v0 \oplus v1 is an ideal))
Proof:
  x is an element of I \oplus J
  for all v0, (if v0 is an element of I \oplus J then x + v0 is an element of I \oplus J)
  Proof:
    y is an element of I \oplus J
    k is an element of I and l is an element of J and x is equal to k + l
    m is an element of I and n is an element of J and y is equal to m + n
    k + m is an element of I and l + n is an element of J
    x + y is equal to k + m + l + n
    Proof:
      x + y is equal to k + m + l + n
    Qed.
    the thesis holds
  Qed.
  for all v0, (if v0 is an object then v0 \cdot x is an element of I \oplus J)
  Proof:
    z is an object
    k is an element of I and l is an element of J and x is equal to k + l
    z \cdot k is an element of I and z \cdot l is an element of J
    z \cdot x is equal to z \cdot k + z \cdot l
    Proof:
      z \cdot x is equal to z \cdot k + z \cdot l
    Qed.
    the thesis holds
  Qed.
Qed.

Theorem (ideint):
  for all v0, (for all v1, (if v0 is an ideal and v1 is an ideal then v0 \cap v1 is an ideal))
Proof:
  x is an element of I \cap J
  for all v0, (if v0 is an element of I \cap J then x + v0 is an element of I \cap J)
  for all v0, (if v0 is an object then v0 \cdot x is an element of I \cap J)
Qed.

Definition (defmod):
  for all v0, (for all v1, (for all v2, (if v0 is an ideal and v1 is an object and v2 is an object then ((v1 = v2 ~(\mod v0 )) iff v1 + - v2 is an element of v0))))

Theorem (chineseremainder):
  for all v0, (for all v1, (if v0 is an ideal and v1 is an ideal then (if for all v2, (if v2 is an object then v2 is an element of v0 \oplus v1) then for all v2, (for all v3, (if v2 is an object and v3 is an object then for some v4, (v4 is an object and v4 = v2 ~(\mod v0 ) and v4 = v3 ~(\mod v1 )))))))
Proof:
  a is an element of I and b is an element of J and a + b is equal to 1
  w is equal to y \cdot a + x \cdot b
  w = x ~(\mod I ) and w = y ~(\mod J )
  Proof:
    w + - x is an element of I
    Proof:
      w + - x is equal to y \cdot a + x \cdot b + - x
      x \cdot b + - 1 is an element of I
      x \cdot b + - 1 is equal to x \cdot b + - x
    Qed.
    w + - y is an element of J
    Proof:
      w + - y is equal to x \cdot b + y \cdot a + - y
      y \cdot a + - 1 is an element of J
      y \cdot a + - 1 is equal to y \cdot a + - y
    Qed.
  Qed.
Qed.

